    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for explaining that. so it's basically just a middleman holding the money? i'm a bit worried about how they decide when it's actually safe to release it to the seller. like, how do they know everything is legit and not some mistake?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right to be cautious, but rest assured, the \"middleman\" isn't just holding cash; they are a highly regulated professional (often a title company or lawyer) who acts as a neutral guardian. They don't just decide when to release funds based on a whim; they follow a strict checklist of conditions, which is why you'll receive an \"Escrow Report\" or \"Closing Disclosure\" detailing every step, such as the final inspection, the transfer of taxes, and the payoff of the seller's mortgage.\n\nTo answer your fear about mistakes: every document is carefully reviewed by professionals, and the process is designed to be transparent. If something were missing or wrong, the escrow agent would flag it immediately, and the deal would pause until it was fixed, preventing any fraud or errors from happening. It's a very safe system, but even with all these safeguards, it's always good to double-check the details yourself.\n\nThink of it like a very strict, no-nonsense security guard who won't let anyone leave the vault until every single lock is clicked shut and every condition is met. If you have any doubts about the process, you can always ask your realtor or the escrow agent for a copy",
